"{\"value\":{\"mdx\":\"# Architecture\\n\\nAt a high level, the ZCAM sdk allows the integrating app to take a picture, generate and sign a valid C2PA manifest over the photo including a signature over the image using the device key, and finally generate a verifiable SP1 proof that the signature is valid, was signed using the key corresponding to the app and corresponds to a given photo.\\n\\nThe core flow uses cryptographic keys that are stored on the devices secure enclave to sign and attest that a photo was indeed taken using the devices camera and has not been tampered with in anyway.\\n\\n## Lifecycle of a zphoto\\n\\nThere are three steps to producing a zphoto (i.e. a photo that can be verified as authentic).\\n\\n| Photo type | Purpose | Context | C2PA Compatible | C2PA Assertion |\\n| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |\\n| Raw | Raw photo, to be proven | Original photo taken by phone, including metadata. No verifiable, attested traits | No | N/A |\\n| Provable | Intermediate state, can be used to actually prove the validity of the photo | Embeds a C2PA manifest including required inputs for generating a zero knowledge proof. This includes a signature using an Apple attested key. | Yes | `succinct.bindings` |\\n| zphoto (i.e. Verifiable) | Final outputted photo that can be verified as authentic | Embeds a C2PA manifest including a verifiable zero knowledge proof that the photo was signed using a valid Apple attested key | Yes | `succinct.proof` |\\n\\n## Key Generation\\n\\nThe ZCAM architecture generates and leverages two keys: A *device* key and a *content* key.\\n\\n- **Device key**: An *Apple Attested* key that signs over a hash of the photo\\n- **Content key**: The key that is used to sign the actual content manifest for C2PA\\n\\nBoth of these keys live in the secure enclave of the Iphone device. Importantly, the device key is specifically attested to have been generated on the secure enclave, and is *specifically* scoped to the SDK.\\n\\n## Steps\\n\\n### Initialization\\n\\nThe SDK first gets initialized. The main logic here is to generate or load the two aforementioned necessary keys.\\n\\n### Capture\\n\\nThe capture step allows a user to use the SDK to take a photo and output a *provable* photo.\\n\\nWhen a user wants to take a zphoto, the sdk will open the camera screen to take a photo.\\n\\nAfter the photo is taken, the sdk will embed a valid C2PA manifest by doing the following:\\n\\n1. First, the photo is hashed, then signed using the device key. It outputs an Apple Attest assertion including a signature over the hash. This is the main *assertion* for the manifest.\\n2. The manifest is then initialized with a *capture* action including metadata of the photo including time of photo, OS, device model, software version etc.\\n3. A `succinct.bindings` assertion is added to the manifest including data necessary to prove that the photo was signed using a valid Apple attested key.\\n\\nNote the output of this step is a photo with a valid C2PA manifest. The C2PA manifest includes metadata about the photo and also an assertion that the photo was signed with an apple attested key.\\n\\n### Prove\\n\\nThe next step is to take the photo w/ C2PA manifest and generating a proof that verifies the validity of said photo. This is done by using the SP1 Prover Network to run the ZCAM proof given the photo (and C2PA manifest) as input to the proof.\\n\\nThe SDK receives the proof from the network, then updates the photo and C2PA manifest. The assertion is removed from the manifest, and instead a *proof* assertion is added that includes the verifiable proof. This is the final photo with a valid C2PA manifest including a verifiable proof.\\n\\n#### What is actually proven\\n\\n1. Takes in photo bytes as input\\n2. Extracts manifest from photo bytes\\n    - Extracts bindings + data hash from manifest\\n3. Computes photo hash from photo\\n4. Checks data hash against photo hash\\n    - Guarantees that the manifest is for the photo\\n5. Check attestation\\n    - Essentially guarantees:\\n        - The device key was generated in a genuine Apple Secure Enclave\\n        - The key is bound to a specific app (via app_id / RP ID)\\n        - The device is running the legitimate app (AAGUID = \\\"appattest\\\" or \\\"appattestdevelop\\\")\\n    - Validates:\\n        - Verifies certificate chain up to Apple Root CA\\n        - Checks nonce matches the challenge\\n        - Confirms public key hash matches the key ID\\n        - Validates RP ID == SHA256(app_id)\\n        - Checks AAGUID is valid Apple attestation identifier\\n6. Check assertion\\n    - Essentially guarantees:\\n        - The photo corresponding to this hash was taken on using ZCAM sdk\\n    - Validates:\\n        - This photo hash was signed by the attested key\\n\\n### Verify\\n\\nFinally, the SDK includes logic for parsing and verifying the proof from the C2PA manifest. This includes methods for pulling the manifest from the photo, verifying the proof in the manifest, pulling the hash and verifying the hash.\\n\",\"document\":[{\"href\":\"/architecture#architecture\",\"html\":\"</header>\\n<p>At a high level, the ZCAM sdk allows the integrating app to take a picture, generate and sign a valid C2PA manifest over the photo including a signature over the image using the device key, and finally generate a verifiable SP1 proof that the signature is valid, was signed using the key corresponding to the app and corresponds to a given photo.</p>\\n<p>The core flow uses cryptographic keys that are stored on the devices secure enclave to sign and attest that a photo was indeed taken using the devices camera and has not been tampered with in anyway.</p>\\n\",\"id\":\"docs/pages/architecture.mdx#architecture\",\"isPage\":true,\"text\":\"\\nAt a high level, the ZCAM sdk allows the integrating app to take a picture, generate and sign a valid C2PA manifest over the photo including a signature over the image using the device key, and finally generate a verifiable SP1 proof that the signature is valid, was signed using the key corresponding to the app and corresponds to a given photo.\\nThe core flow uses cryptographic keys that are stored on the devices secure enclave to sign and attest that a photo was indeed taken using the devices camera and has not been tampered with in anyway.\\n\",\"title\":\"Architecture\",\"titles\":[]},{\"href\":\"/architecture#lifecycle-of-a-zphoto\",\"html\":\"\\n<p>There are three steps to producing a zphoto (i.e. a photo that can be verified as authentic).</p>\\n<table><thead><tr><th>Photo type</th><th>Purpose</th><th>Context</th><th>C2PA Compatible</th><th>C2PA Assertion</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Raw</td><td>Raw photo, to be proven</td><td>Original photo taken by phone, including metadata. No verifiable, attested traits</td><td>No</td><td>N/A</td></tr><tr><td>Provable</td><td>Intermediate state, can be used to actually prove the validity of the photo</td><td>Embeds a C2PA manifest including required inputs for generating a zero knowledge proof. This includes a signature using an Apple attested key.</td><td>Yes</td><td><code>succinct.bindings</code></td></tr><tr><td>zphoto (i.e. Verifiable)</td><td>Final outputted photo that can be verified as authentic</td><td>Embeds a C2PA manifest including a verifiable zero knowledge proof that the photo was signed using a valid Apple attested key</td><td>Yes</td><td><code>succinct.proof</code></td></tr></tbody></table>\\n\",\"id\":\"docs/pages/architecture.mdx#lifecycle-of-a-zphoto\",\"isPage\":false,\"text\":\"\\nThere are three steps to producing a zphoto (i.e. a photo that can be verified as authentic).\\nPhoto typePurposeContextC2PA CompatibleC2PA AssertionRawRaw photo, to be provenOriginal photo taken by phone, including metadata. No verifiable, attested traitsNoN/AProvableIntermediate state, can be used to actually prove the validity of the photoEmbeds a C2PA manifest including required inputs for generating a zero knowledge proof. This includes a signature using an Apple attested key.Yessuccinct.bindingszphoto (i.e. Verifiable)Final outputted photo that can be verified as authenticEmbeds a C2PA manifest including a verifiable zero knowledge proof that the photo was signed using a valid Apple attested keyYessuccinct.proof\\n\",\"title\":\"Lifecycle of a zphoto\",\"titles\":[\"Architecture\"]},{\"href\":\"/architecture#key-generation\",\"html\":\"\\n<p>The ZCAM architecture generates and leverages two keys: A <em>device</em> key and a <em>content</em> key.</p>\\n<ul>\\n<li><strong>Device key</strong>: An <em>Apple Attested</em> key that signs over a hash of the photo</li>\\n<li><strong>Content key</strong>: The key that is used to sign the actual content manifest for C2PA</li>\\n</ul>\\n<p>Both of these keys live in the secure enclave of the Iphone device. Importantly, the device key is specifically attested to have been generated on the secure enclave, and is <em>specifically</em> scoped to the SDK.</p>\\n\",\"id\":\"docs/pages/architecture.mdx#key-generation\",\"isPage\":false,\"text\":\"\\nThe ZCAM architecture generates and leverages two keys: A device key and a content key.\\n\\nDevice key: An Apple Attested key that signs over a hash of the photo\\nContent key: The key that is used to sign the actual content manifest for C2PA\\n\\nBoth of these keys live in the secure enclave of the Iphone device. Importantly, the device key is specifically attested to have been generated on the secure enclave, and is specifically scoped to the SDK.\\n\",\"title\":\"Key Generation\",\"titles\":[\"Architecture\"]},{\"href\":\"/architecture#steps\",\"html\":\"\\n\",\"id\":\"docs/pages/architecture.mdx#steps\",\"isPage\":false,\"text\":\"\\n\",\"title\":\"Steps\",\"titles\":[\"Architecture\"]},{\"href\":\"/architecture#initialization\",\"html\":\"\\n<p>The SDK first gets initialized. The main logic here is to generate or load the two aforementioned necessary keys.</p>\\n\",\"id\":\"docs/pages/architecture.mdx#initialization\",\"isPage\":false,\"text\":\"\\nThe SDK first gets initialized. The main logic here is to generate or load the two aforementioned necessary keys.\\n\",\"title\":\"Initialization\",\"titles\":[\"Architecture\",\"Steps\"]},{\"href\":\"/architecture#capture\",\"html\":\"\\n<p>The capture step allows a user to use the SDK to take a photo and output a <em>provable</em> photo.</p>\\n<p>When a user wants to take a zphoto, the sdk will open the camera screen to take a photo.</p>\\n<p>After the photo is taken, the sdk will embed a valid C2PA manifest by doing the following:</p>\\n<ol>\\n<li>First, the photo is hashed, then signed using the device key. It outputs an Apple Attest assertion including a signature over the hash. This is the main <em>assertion</em> for the manifest.</li>\\n<li>The manifest is then initialized with a <em>capture</em> action including metadata of the photo including time of photo, OS, device model, software version etc.</li>\\n<li>A <code>succinct.bindings</code> assertion is added to the manifest including data necessary to prove that the photo was signed using a valid Apple attested key.</li>\\n</ol>\\n<p>Note the output of this step is a photo with a valid C2PA manifest. The C2PA manifest includes metadata about the photo and also an assertion that the photo was signed with an apple attested key.</p>\\n\",\"id\":\"docs/pages/architecture.mdx#capture\",\"isPage\":false,\"text\":\"\\nThe capture step allows a user to use the SDK to take a photo and output a provable photo.\\nWhen a user wants to take a zphoto, the sdk will open the camera screen to take a photo.\\nAfter the photo is taken, the sdk will embed a valid C2PA manifest by doing the following:\\n\\nFirst, the photo is hashed, then signed using the device key. It outputs an Apple Attest assertion including a signature over the hash. This is the main assertion for the manifest.\\nThe manifest is then initialized with a capture action including metadata of the photo including time of photo, OS, device model, software version etc.\\nA succinct.bindings assertion is added to the manifest including data necessary to prove that the photo was signed using a valid Apple attested key.\\n\\nNote the output of this step is a photo with a valid C2PA manifest. The C2PA manifest includes metadata about the photo and also an assertion that the photo was signed with an apple attested key.\\n\",\"title\":\"Capture\",\"titles\":[\"Architecture\",\"Steps\"]},{\"href\":\"/architecture#prove\",\"html\":\"\\n<p>The next step is to take the photo w/ C2PA manifest and generating a proof that verifies the validity of said photo. This is done by using the SP1 Prover Network to run the ZCAM proof given the photo (and C2PA manifest) as input to the proof.</p>\\n<p>The SDK receives the proof from the network, then updates the photo and C2PA manifest. The assertion is removed from the manifest, and instead a <em>proof</em> assertion is added that includes the verifiable proof. This is the final photo with a valid C2PA manifest including a verifiable proof.</p>\\n\",\"id\":\"docs/pages/architecture.mdx#prove\",\"isPage\":false,\"text\":\"\\nThe next step is to take the photo w/ C2PA manifest and generating a proof that verifies the validity of said photo. This is done by using the SP1 Prover Network to run the ZCAM proof given the photo (and C2PA manifest) as input to the proof.\\nThe SDK receives the proof from the network, then updates the photo and C2PA manifest. The assertion is removed from the manifest, and instead a proof assertion is added that includes the verifiable proof. This is the final photo with a valid C2PA manifest including a verifiable proof.\\n\",\"title\":\"Prove\",\"titles\":[\"Architecture\",\"Steps\"]},{\"href\":\"/architecture#what-is-actually-proven\",\"html\":\"\\n<ol>\\n<li>Takes in photo bytes as input</li>\\n<li>Extracts manifest from photo bytes\\n<ul>\\n<li>Extracts bindings + data hash from manifest</li>\\n</ul>\\n</li>\\n<li>Computes photo hash from photo</li>\\n<li>Checks data hash against photo hash\\n<ul>\\n<li>Guarantees that the manifest is for the photo</li>\\n</ul>\\n</li>\\n<li>Check attestation\\n<ul>\\n<li>Essentially guarantees:\\n<ul>\\n<li>The device key was generated in a genuine Apple Secure Enclave</li>\\n<li>The key is bound to a specific app (via app_id / RP ID)</li>\\n<li>The device is running the legitimate app (AAGUID = &quot;appattest&quot; or &quot;appattestdevelop&quot;)</li>\\n</ul>\\n</li>\\n<li>Validates:\\n<ul>\\n<li>Verifies certificate chain up to Apple Root CA</li>\\n<li>Checks nonce matches the challenge</li>\\n<li>Confirms public key hash matches the key ID</li>\\n<li>Validates RP ID == SHA256(app_id)</li>\\n<li>Checks AAGUID is valid Apple attestation identifier</li>\\n</ul>\\n</li>\\n</ul>\\n</li>\\n<li>Check assertion\\n<ul>\\n<li>Essentially guarantees:\\n<ul>\\n<li>The photo corresponding to this hash was taken on using ZCAM sdk</li>\\n</ul>\\n</li>\\n<li>Validates:\\n<ul>\\n<li>This photo hash was signed by the attested key</li>\\n</ul>\\n</li>\\n</ul>\\n</li>\\n</ol>\\n\",\"id\":\"docs/pages/architecture.mdx#what-is-actually-proven\",\"isPage\":false,\"text\":\"\\n\\nTakes in photo bytes as input\\nExtracts manifest from photo bytes\\n\\nExtracts bindings + data hash from manifest\\n\\n\\nComputes photo hash from photo\\nChecks data hash against photo hash\\n\\nGuarantees that the manifest is for the photo\\n\\n\\nCheck attestation\\n\\nEssentially guarantees:\\n\\nThe device key was generated in a genuine Apple Secure Enclave\\nThe key is bound to a specific app (via app_id / RP ID)\\nThe device is running the legitimate app (AAGUID = &quot;appattest&quot; or &quot;appattestdevelop&quot;)\\n\\n\\nValidates:\\n\\nVerifies certificate chain up to Apple Root CA\\nChecks nonce matches the challenge\\nConfirms public key hash matches the key ID\\nValidates RP ID == SHA256(app_id)\\nChecks AAGUID is valid Apple attestation identifier\\n\\n\\n\\n\\nCheck assertion\\n\\nEssentially guarantees:\\n\\nThe photo corresponding to this hash was taken on using ZCAM sdk\\n\\n\\nValidates:\\n\\nThis photo hash was signed by the attested key\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\",\"title\":\"What is actually proven\",\"titles\":[\"Architecture\",\"Steps\",\"Prove\"]},{\"href\":\"/architecture#verify\",\"html\":\"\\n<p>Finally, the SDK includes logic for parsing and verifying the proof from the C2PA manifest. This includes methods for pulling the manifest from the photo, verifying the proof in the manifest, pulling the hash and verifying the hash.</p>\",\"id\":\"docs/pages/architecture.mdx#verify\",\"isPage\":false,\"text\":\"\\nFinally, the SDK includes logic for parsing and verifying the proof from the C2PA manifest. This includes methods for pulling the manifest from the photo, verifying the proof in the manifest, pulling the hash and verifying the hash.\",\"title\":\"Verify\",\"titles\":[\"Architecture\",\"Steps\"]}]}}"
